content.div:
Former Miss America second runner up Elyse Umemoto was blind-sided when she became the most recent contestant eliminated from Survivor: South Pacific. As a member of one of the Savaii tribe's strongest alliances, the 27-year-old was sacrificed as part of a coup against group leader Ozzy led by her former alliance member Jim. Speaking from a bench in a convention centre in San Diego, the Las Vegas resident talks to Dose.ca about why she refuses to watch the show and what really happened between her and Ozzy.

You’re one of the first contestants eliminated that fans of the show really got to hear from and know. What did you think about the way you were portrayed?

I have not seen an episode of Survivor: South Pacific to date. It’s bitterly uncomfortable for me to watch myself on TV. I remember it took me a long time to be able to watch the video from Miss America, and I’m happier than a clam to finish second runner up -- very few people will be top three of Miss America – but it makes me uncomfortable. Also, I’d like to be able to watch the whole season in its entirety as one big epic. I will watch it for the sake of knowing what’s going on before we get to the finale.

Have you managed to piece together what happened?

I’ve seen snippets of the show that my friends, parents and second grade teachers – everybody comes out of the woodwork when something like this happens -- sent me, knowing I don’t watch. So I do know what happens in the last two episodes.

Do you feel any resentment about the way things went down?

No, I know it’s part of the game. I was loosely aligned with Jim at the beginning of the game and then when people picked up that me and Ozzy were in an alliance I think things got ugly from there. I can’t hold it against anyone, especially Jim, for pulling some kind of scheme because, if hadn’t done it to me, I was going to do something to him; he just beat me to the punch.

So you feel it was just part of the game

It is. I can’t imagine losing sleep over any of this.

So what really happened between you and Ozzy?

Oh, you want all the gritty details? Prepare yourself…we were just homies.

C’mon…

I swear. Trust and believe. We have a lot in common. I think my personality connected with his more than anybody else in the group. He’s a west coaster, he’s multiracial, he’s involved in philanthropy. We just happened to get along the best of everyone in the group and I just thanked my lucky stars that the strongest player in the game said that he and I should match up, we could go far together.

Are you surprised that Cochran has managed to continue to elude eviction?

Yeah, he’s a little something, isn’t he?! Looking back and knowing what I know, what I can say about Cochran is that I don’t think any of us gave him enough credit early enough in the game to realize what he’s capable of. I’ve got a feeling he’s going a long way. If I were a fan of the show I’d be really pulling for this guy because he plays a good game.

Finally, who do you think will end up with the million dollars?

God, I hope it’s Christine! I would think it’s worse to weather it out there on Redemption Island, alone in your head than it is to be with a crowd back with your tribe. She’s got nothing but love from me.
